1. Conditional Expection and Least Square Regression¶

Let $X$ and $Y$ be two random variables. The conditional expectation $\mathbb{E}\left[Y|X\right]$ is a function $f^{\ast}$ of $X$ that best approximates $Y$ in the least square sense, i.e.,

$$\mathbb{E}\left[Y|X\right]=f^{\ast}(X)\quad\text{and}\quad\mathbb{E}\left[\left|Y-f^{\ast}(X)\right|^2\right]\leq\mathbb{E}\left[\left|Y-f(X)\right|^2\right]\text{ for any function }f\text{ of }X$$

Let us define the random variables $X$ and $Y$ by $$ g(x) = x \frac{1 + x}{1 + x^2}, \qquad X \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1), \quad Y = g(X) + \varepsilon $$ where $\varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1/16)$ is independent of $X$.

Note that $\mathbb{E}\left[\left.Y\right|X\right] = \mathbb{E}\left[\left.g(X)+\varepsilon\right|X\right] = g(X)+\mathbb{E}\left[\left.\varepsilon\right|X\right] = g(X)$.

Parametric regression¶

The conditional expection $\mathbb{E}\left[\left.Y\right|X\right]$ is approximated by a linear combination of a set of given basis functions $\{f_i(X)\}_{0\leq i\leq n}$, i.e.,

$$\mathbb{E}\left[Y|X\right]\approx \beta_0^*f_0(X)+\cdots+\beta_n^*f_n(X)$$

where

$$\mathbb{E}\left[\left(Y-\beta_0^*f_0(X)-\cdots-\beta_n^*f_n(X)\right)^2\right] = \min_{\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_n}\mathbb{E}\left[\left(Y-\beta_0f_0(X)-\cdots-\beta_nf_n(X)\right)^2\right]$$

Given $N$ observations $\left((x_1,y_1),\ldots,(x_N, y_N)\right)$ of $X$ and $Y$, one finds the optimal parameters $\beta_i$ by solving the least square problem $\min_\beta\|A\beta-y\|_2$, where $$A=\begin{bmatrix}f_0(x_1) & \cdots & f_n(x_1)\\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ f_0(x_N) & \cdots & f_n(x_N)\end{bmatrix}\quad \text{and}\quad y=\begin{bmatrix}y_1\\ \vdots \\ y_N\end{bmatrix}$$

The numpy routine numpy.linalg.lstsq can be used to solve such linear least square problems.

Polynomials¶

The basis functions are taken to be power functions $f_i(X)=X^{i}$, that is $\mathbb{E}\left[Y|X\right]$ is a polynomial of $X$. The numpy routine numpy.polyfit is a convenient way to obtain the least square polynomial fit.

Laguerre Polynomials¶

The Laguerre polynomials are defined by

$$L_n(x)=\frac{1}{n!}\left(\frac{d}{dx}-1\right)^nx^n.$$

In particular, we have

$$L_0(x)=1,\quad L_1(x)=-x+1,\quad L_2(x)=\frac{1}{2}\left(x^2-4x+2\right),\quad\cdots$$

They are orthogonal polynomials with respect to the inner product $\langle f, g\rangle=\int_0^{\infty}f(x)g(x)e^{-x}dx$. Therefore we will be actually using the weighted version

$$\tilde{L}_n(x)=e^{-x/2}L_n(x)$$

Piecewise Linear Regression¶

In [5]:
def pwlinear_basis(xknots):
    """Basis that represent a piecewise linear function with given knots"""
    fs = [lambda x: np.ones_like(x, dtype=np.float), lambda x: x-xknots[0]]
    fs.extend([lambda x, a=xknots[i]: np.maximum(x-a, 0) for i in range(len(xknots))])
    return fs

def pwlinear_fit(xdata, ydata, xknots):
    """Fit a piecewise linear function with xknots to xdata and ydata"""
    fs = pwlinear_basis(xknots)
    A = np.vstack([f(xdata) for f in fs]).T
    ps = np.linalg.lstsq(A, ydata, rcond=None)[0]
    return ps, fs

Nonparametric regression¶

Nadaraya-Watson Kernel regression (Local Weighted Average)¶

Here, no parametric form is assumed for $\mathbb{E}[Y|X]$. Instead, local averages of $Y$ values are computed, given the value of $X$:

$$\mathbb{E}\left[Y|X\right]\approx\frac{\sum_{i=1}^NK_h(x-x_i)y_i}{\sum_{i=1}^NK_h(x-x_i)}$$

where $K$ is a kernel function and $K_h(x)=K(x/h)$, $h$ is the bandwidth. $K_h$ approximates the Dirac mass at zero.

Local Linear Regression¶

The locally weighted linear regression solves a separate weighted least squares problem at each target point $x$,

$$\hat{\alpha},\hat{\beta} = \text{argmin}_{\alpha,\beta}\sum_{i=1}^NK_h(x-x_i)\left[y_i-\alpha-\beta x_i\right]^2$$

which yields an estimate $\hat{\alpha}+\hat{\beta}x$. Note that $\hat{\alpha}$ and $\hat{\beta}$ depend on $x$. The locally-weighted averages can be badly biased on the boundaries. This bias can be removed by local linear regression to the first order.

Note. To speed up, we often perform the local regression only at a selection of points and then use interpolation/extrapolation to evaluate at other target points.

In [7]:
# Non-parametric regression function

def gauss_kern(x):
    """Gaussian kernel function"""
    return np.exp(-x**2/2)

def kern_reg(x, xdata, ydata, bandwidth, kern=gauss_kern):
    """Nadaraya-Watson Kernel Regression (Locally weighted average)

    Parameters
    ----------
    x: array_like, one-dimensional
        The x-coordinates of the target points
    xdata: array_like
        The x-coordinates of the data points.
    ydata: array_like
        The y-coordinates of the data points. 
    bandwidth: positive scalar
        Bandwidth of the kernel
    kern: callable
        kernel function
    """
    weights = kern((xdata[:, np.newaxis] - x) / bandwidth)
    return np.sum(weights * ydata[:, np.newaxis], axis=0) / np.sum(weights, axis=0)


def ll_reg(x, xdata, ydata, bandwidth, kern=gauss_kern):
    """Local Linear Regression

    Parameters
    ----------
    x: array_like, one-dimensional
        The x-coordinates of the target points
    xdata: array_like
        The x-coordinates of the data points.
    ydata: array_like
        The y-coordinates of the data points. 
    bandwidth: positive scalar
        Bandwidth of the kernel
    kern: callable
        kernel function
    """
    
    def func(xx):
        weights = np.sqrt(kern((xdata-xx)/bandwidth))
        b = ydata*weights
        A = np.vstack((np.ones_like(xdata), xdata-xx)).T*weights[:, np.newaxis]
        yy, _ = np.linalg.lstsq(A, b, rcond=None)[0]
        return yy
    
    return np.vectorize(func)(x)

  • The 4th degree polynomial used usually led to the best match the true function, yet still shows some overfitting and large deviations at the boundaries. Although none of the polynomial fits will be perfect, this curve showed strong accuracy in the region where the data points are mostly concentrated.

  • It is clear from the progression of the polynomial curves, that as the degree increases, the overfitting to spurious data points, increased number of inflection points, and oscillatory phenomenom lead to large deviations from the true function, but depending on the particular data points in the vector X, the higher degree polynomials may not have large deviations at the extreme ends of the data range.

For the piecewise linear regression I tested using 2, 5, 8, 10, and 12 knots, all equally spaced from the 5th to 95th percentile of the input data, just like in the example given.

  • The regression with two knots, although with moderate deviations at most locations due to inflexibility of the curve, was able to generally follow the true function's shape. The performance seems in line with the lower order polynomial fits, but the piecewise linear regression also could have fit the curve even better if the knots were chosen closer to the true function's extrema.

  • In the regresion with five knots, the knots were well dispersed throughout the data range and thus were able to capture the general shape of the function extremely accurately compared to the polynomial regressions. Especially in ranges where many data points appeared, the linear regressions were able to find fits very close to the true function. In the regions where the data was more dispersed, the linear regression led to fits that were less accurate, but still close to the true function.

  • In using 8, 10, and 12 knots, the curves resulting from the regression looked very similar. As the number of knots increased, the more there was 'oscillatory' behavior in the overall curve, as the piece by piece linear regressions began to overfit to data due to the smaller ranges in which the regressions occurred. This meant that using 5 knots was the best choice in most situations, rather than using higher values of knots. This could be remedied by choosing knots that were not equidistant, but this would not be practical in many situations since we can only make this judgement after observing the form of the true function. The choice of equally spaced knots would be a good standard choice when performing most regressions as it would not 'overweight' any certain region of the data.

  • In general, the piecewise linear regression performed the best out of the 3 types of regressions tested, due to the special characteristic of having knots being placed throughout the data range, and therefore the ability to capture local phenomena without leading to compromises in the rest of the curve. This is not possible in the polynomial curves, where the polynomials must be considered as a whole. For example there are limits on the number of inflection points possible in a polynomial curve of a certain, and when attempting to increase the degree of the polynomial to create a better fit, this often leads to oscillatory behavior and overfitting.

In the Nadaraya-Watson Kernel Regression, I tested bandwidths of 0.01, 0.1, .4, .85, 1.2, 1.5, and 2.

  • For the lowest bandwiths of 0.01 and 0.1, there was extreme overfitting in the curves. This is because the low bandwith means the kernel functions are effectively being 'shrunk' to act in a smaller area and thus being more sensitive to local datapoints. This shows that at lower bandwidths there is very high variance but low bias, as the curves are specialized to this present data set without making many assumptions about the general shape of the true function.

  • In the high bandwidth regions of 0.85, 1.2, 1.5, and 2, the curves are underfitting and extremely general. The curves are tending towards linearity as the bandwidth gets higher and higher, and this can be explained from the high bandwidth which effectively increases the standard deviation of the gaussian kernel function. The estimated probability distributions are therefore much more spread out and lead to smoother curves in both the kernel density estimation and in the kernel regression.

  • The bandwidth of 0.4, very close to the Silverman rule of thumb bandwidth, led to the best results. This curve had some regions of larger deviations, but was generally able to follow the shape of the curve very well. This shows that the bias-variance tradeoff in regression is very important, especially in kernel regression, where the bandwidths can be easily modified to totally change the effectiveness of a particular regression. A balance between bias and variance is necessary to avoid overfitting and underfitting, and minimizing the mean integrated square error is able to perform this task well.

  • In general the kernel regression at the 0.4 bandwidth performed well compared to the polynomial, laguerre polynomial, and piecewise linear regressions. Using 5 equally spaced knots in the piecewise linear regression might be preferred to this 0.4 bandwidth kernel regression as it more closely follows the true function in the range where the data points are most heavily distributed.

Kernels¶

In [13]:
def Example(x):
    """Example kernel function"""
    def func(x):
        if (-1.0 <= x <= 1): return ((x+1.0)**2.0) * ((1.0-x)**2.0)
        else: return 0.0
    return np.vectorize(func)(x)

def Modified_Example(x):
    """Example kernel function with terms added rather than multiplied"""
    def func(x):
        if (-1.0 <= x <= 1): return ((x+1.0)**2.0) + ((1.0-x)**2.0)
        else: return 0.0
    return np.vectorize(func)(x)

def Quartic(x):
    """Quartic kernel function"""
    def func(x):
        if (-1.0 <= x <= 1): return (15.0/16.0)*((1.0 + x)**2.0)*((1.0 - x)**2.0)
        else: return 0
    return np.vectorize(func)(x)

def Epanechnikov(x):
    """Epanechnikov( kernel function"""
    def func(x):
        if (-1.0 <= x <= 1): return (3.0/4.0) *((1.0 - (x**2.0)))
        else: return 0
    return np.vectorize(func)(x)

def Gaussian(x):
    """Gaussian kernel function"""
    return np.exp(-x**2/2)

def Triweight(x):
    """Triweight kernel function"""
    def func(x):
        if (-1.0 <= x <= 1): return (35.0/32.0)*((1.0 - (x**2.0))**3.0)
        else: return 0
    return np.vectorize(func)(x)

I tried using the following Kernels: Gaussian, the kernel in the problem, the kernel in the problem with the terms added $K(x)=(x+1)^2 + (1-x)^2$, the Quartic kernel, $K(x) = \frac{15}{16}(1+x)^2(1-x)^2$, Epanechnikov kernel, $K(x) = \frac{3}{4}(1-x^2)$, and the Triweight kernel $K(x) = \frac{35}{32}(1-x^2)^3$. All of the kernels except for the Gaussian kernel had bounded support (on $-1\leq x\leq 1$). For each of these kernels I tried several different bandwidth values, but display only some of the interesting/relevant bandwidths.

  • The Gaussian kernel as explained before, performs best around the $~0.4$ bandwidth range, due to the optimization of the bias-variance tradeoff. Compared to the other kernels, the Gaussian kernel is much smoother as well, due to not having a bounded support, and thus the kernel functions sum up with less jumps.

  • The kernel given in the problem had the issue that for lower bandwidths, the denominator in the kernel regression, $\sum_{i=1}^NK_h(x-x_i)$, was $0$. This meant that the division in the NW regression led to NaN for certain target points, and therefore discontinuities in the graph. In most cases, for a given bandwidth, NaN was the value for all target points and thus nothing at all was plotted. As the bandwidth was greatly increased, to around 3.5, the NaN issue was resolved, but by this point the curve was greatly underfit to the data. The higher bandwidths has too much bias and could not specialize to the data effectively.

  • The modified kernel I used where the terms were added instead, performed better than the unmodified kernel, due to the removal of the NaN issue. Again, bandwidths around $~0.5$ were better, while higher bandwidths led to too much bias, although the curves were also smoother. The $0.5$ bandwidth curve was very jagged, and although the jaggedness followed the general shape of the curve, there would be large variations in predicted values for inputs in a small range.

  • The quartic and epanechnikov kernels had the same issue as the kernel given in the problem. For smaller bandwidths, there were NaN values and thus no curve, and once an appropriate bandwidth was reached, the regression was underfit and too biased to be of value.

  • The triweight kernel was interesting in that, for certain data point vectors X, for lower bandwiths, it had NaN values for certain target points, while not for others, thus leading to a curve with 'blanks'. At around certain higher bandwidths, the NaN issue was resolved, and the curve was very similar to the modified kernel I created above. So at bandwidths high enough to not have NaN values, the curve was very jagged and seemed to have high variance, although the general shape of the true function was followed. This was the case until at some slightly higher bandwidth the curve became underfit, and appeared almost linear with some curvature at the extreme ends, just like in the quartic and epanechnikov kernels.

  • Overall, I think that bandwidth is the primary factor in determining the effectiveness of a regression. The bandwidth determines the trade-off between bias and variance, due to the property of kernel functions having bounded support and thus only resulting in non-zero values for only a certain range of inputs. This means that a low bandwidth will lead to very high variance but low bias, and higher bandwidths are more biased but smoother/less variance. Even if the kernel is suitably chosen, an improper selection of bandwidth will lead to very poor predictions of the true function values, and so, bandwidth selection is essential. This effect is exacerbated in the kernels with bounded support, as too low a bandwidth will lead to $0$s in the denominator and thus division by zero issues.

  • Selecting an appropriate kernel is also important in kernel regression, as can be seen in the differences between the Gaussian kernel and the kernels that have bounded support. But in general, it seems that, once a proper bandwidth is chosen, the kernels of bounded support have similar properties (in terms of variance and overall fit), again highlighting the importance of bandwidth selection.

def blackscholes_mc(S=100, vol=0.2, r=0, q=0, ts=np.linspace(0, 1, 13), npaths=10):
    """Generate Monte-Carlo paths in Black-Scholes model.

    Parameters
    ----------
    S: scalar
        The spot price of the underlying security.
    vol: scalar
        The implied Black-Scholes volatility.
    r: scalar
        The annualized risk-free interest rate, continuously compounded.
    q: scalar
        The annualized continuous dividend yield.
    ts: array_like
        The time steps of the simualtion
    npaths: int
        the number of paths to simulate

    Returns
    -------
    paths: ndarray
        The Monte-Carlo paths.
    """
    nsteps = len(ts) - 1
    ts = np.asfarray(ts)[:, np.newaxis]
    W = np.cumsum(np.vstack((np.zeros((1, npaths), dtype=np.float),
                             np.random.randn(nsteps, npaths) * np.sqrt(np.diff(ts, axis=0)))),
                  axis=0)
    paths = np.exp(-0.5*vol**2*ts + vol*W)*S*np.exp((r-q)*ts)
    return paths

def blackscholes_price(K, T, S, vol, r=0, q=0, callput='call'):
    """Compute the call/put option price in the Black-Scholes model
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    K: scalar or array_like
        The strike of the option.
    T: scalar or array_like
        The maturity of the option, expressed in years (e.g. 0.25 for 3-month and 2 for 2 years)
    S: scalar or array_like
        The current price of the underlying asset.
    vol: scalar or array_like
        The implied Black-Scholes volatility.
    r: scalar or array_like
        The annualized risk-free interest rate, continuously compounded.
    q: scalar or array_like
        The annualized continuous dividend yield.
    callput: str
        Must be either 'call' or 'put'.

    Returns
    -------
    price: scalar or array_like
        The price of the option.

    Examples
    --------
    >>> blackscholes_price(95, 0.25, 100, 0.2, r=0.05, callput='put')
    1.5342604771222823
    """
    F = S*np.exp((r-q)*T)
    v = np.sqrt(vol**2*T)
    d1 = np.log(F/K)/v + 0.5*v
    d2 = d1 - v
    try:
        opttype = {'call':1, 'put':-1}[callput.lower()]
    except:
        raise ValueError('The value of callput must be either "call" or "put".')
    price = opttype*(F*norm.cdf(opttype*d1)-K*norm.cdf(opttype*d2))*np.exp(-r*T)
    return price

Question 2.2. Both TVR and Longstaff-Schwartz algorithms provide an estimate for the expected payoff from continuation at each exercise date from the cross-sectional information in the simulation using regression. By comparing this estimate with the immediate exercise value, the holder of the option can determine whether to exercise the option or continue.

Perform an independent Monte Carlo simulation using this estimate of continuation value from both algorithms as an exercise policy, and estimate the price of the American put. Explain why this estimate is a lower bound. The basis functions for regression can be chosen to be the quadratic polynomial as in the sample code.

Show your code and result with at least 100000 simulations.

Q2.2¶

In general, both the TVR and LS algorithms are solutions to a primal problem, where the goal is to maximize the expectation of a payoff over all possible stopping times. This is analogous to a 'buyer's price' where the option buyer is attempting to calculate what the maximum possible benefit he may receive from owning the option. Since the numerical algorithms are not 'perfect', they can be considered suboptimal, in that the regressions do not precisely predict the conditional expectations and that there is noise in the simulation paths. This leads to an imperfect calculation of the solution to a primal problem (Snell envelope), and since the optimal strategy is a supremum over stopping times, this implies that a suboptimal strategy must lead to a lower value, and thus a lower bound estimate.

Since the TVR and LS algorithms have issues with high bias, the option value predicted will often be higher than the appropriate option price, especially due to exercise decisions and option value being decided based on future values of the simulation. This means that for a given set of simulated paths, whenever the future values are higher or lower than whatever an 'average' value would be, this information is used to determine the decision to exercise and therefore the 'best' decision is made, leading to an increased valuation for the option.

To avoid this issue, low-biased pricing is used, where the continuation values are estimated in one run of the pricing algorithms, and then an independent run of monte carlo simulations is done in order to evaluate what the option price would be without having opportunities to look into the future. So since the low-biased pricing algorithms lead to lower option values and are solutions to a primal problem, the option values resulting are lower bounds.

For the charts of the exercise regions, I included stock prices in an exercise region as long as the continuation value was $\leq$ to the exercise value, regardless of whether the option was ITM, so for negative continuation values, exercise is indicated. Negative continuation values occurred due to $(K-S)^+$ having minimum value 0 and so ITM continuation values were nearer to low values as stock prices went towards the strike price (this is expected due to the characteristic of the underlying Brownian Motion simulated, and its tendency to not expect large price changes from the present stock value, so a higher current stock price implies a lower option value for the future), and the regressors captured this trend by continuing further below 0 in OTM regions. Since we only used ITM support data points, the regression curves are very inaccurate in OTM regions. This is not an issue in most cases, as continuation values are not necessary to be computed in OTM regions, so we allow for inaccurate regression in the OTM region by design.

In general, when regression was done only using ITM support points, the resulting coefficients for the basis functions across the TVR and LS algorithms, (and therefore the overall output for the regressor at a stock price) were very similar. This effect was seen more heavily the higher the number of paths simulated. This characteristic is due to the discounted payouts (LS) and discounted future option value (TVR) being close for deep ITM options. Since the put price converges to the payoff the further deep in the money the stock price goes, and we only regressed on ITM data points, the resulting regressors for both LS and the TVR algorithms ended up similar regardless of whether the polynomial or BS basis functions were used. This is also seen from the final put prices being closer than in the cases where all data points were used as support points.

In ITM regions both types of regression (polynomial and with the BS basis functions) had similar curves, but the polynomial regression was much worse in the deep OTM regions because of the parabolic shape of degree 2 polynomials.

A result that is hard to see without a visual representation is that there is (depending on the sample paths) a region between extremely deep ITM and ITM-but-closer-to-ATM prices where it would be optimal to exercise (using this algorithm and estimated continuation value). This is not a realistic case since the holder of an American option would have exercised the option by that point (assuming no discontinuous jump in the stock price) since the exercise region occurs before this point.

    p1 = np.polyfit(paths[i][itm[0]], discounted[itm[0],:], deg=2).T
    contval_2 = np.polynomial.polynomial.polyval(paths[i][itm[0]], np.flip(p1, axis = 1).T).T

Question 2.5. Use the Longstaff-Schwartz algorithm to price an Bermudan-Asian call option. The underlying security price is assumed to follow the geometric Brownian motion

$$\frac{dS_t}{S_t}=(r-q)dt+\sigma dW_t$$

with $S_0=100$, $r=0$, $q=0$ and $\sigma=0.2$. The option has a strike of $K=100$ and a final expiration date of $T=1$ and can be exercised every month before the final maturity, i.e. $$t_1=\frac{1}{12},\, t_2=\frac{2}{12},\, \ldots,\, t_{12}=1$$

The cashflow from exercising the option at time $t_n$, $n=1,\ldots,12$, is $\max\left(0, A_{t_n}-K\right)$ with $A_{t_n}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nS_{t_i}$.

As the basis functions in the regression at time $t_n$, use the constant 1.0 and the Black-Scholes value of a European call option with strike $K$, maturity $T-t_n$, and volatility $\bar\sigma = 0.1$, written on $$ Z_{t_n}\equiv \frac{nA_{t_n}+(12-n)S_{t_n}}{12} $$

As in Question 2.4, after you have obtained estimations of continuation values from the Longstaff-Schwartz algorithm, run an independent Monte Carlo simulation with at least 100000 paths to obtain a low-biased price. Explain the use of $Z_{t_n}$ instead of simply $A_{t_n}$ or $S_{t_n}$.

$Z_{t_n}$ is used because the Black Scholes value of an European option in the BS model is using a Geometric Brownian Motion. This means that the expected stock price (on non dividend paying stock) at expiration when discounted to the present day (under the risk neutral measure) should be the present stock price. In the case where the interest rate is $0$, this means that the stock price at expiration is expected to be the same as the current stock price. In this sense, when a call option is written on the stock using the BS price, it is implicit that the seller considers the current stock price as a measure of what the stock price may be at expiration.

In the case of the Asian option, the payoff at maturity is not relative to the stock price at maturity, but the average stock price in the 12 months before maturity. So on date $t_n$ the cumulative stock prices thus far is $nA_{t_n}$. From the perspective of the option seller, the option payout at expiration will be the cumulative thus far, plus the remaining amount that accumulates between $t_n$ and maturity. So there are $(12-n)$ months left until maturity, and assuming that the current stock price is expected to stay at its current level (under the risk neutral measure), the expected accumulation by $t_12$ is $nA_{t_n} + (12-n)S_{t_n}$, and so the payout on expiration (as can be best surmised today) would be relative to $Z_{t_n}$ rather than to $S_{t_n}$. So when using the BS value of an European option to try and best predict the conditional expectation of future payoffs for an Asian option, it is as if the European option was written on $Z_{t_n}$ rather than on $S_{t_n}$

for i in range(len(ts)-2, 0, -1):
    discount = np.exp(-r*(ts[i+1]-ts[i]))
    payoff = payoff*discount
    exerval = np.maximum(np.average(paths[1:(i+1),:], axis = 0) - K, 0)
    itm_ind = np.array(np.where(exerval > 0)[0])
    
    #calculate the matrix A for the least squares regression by evaluating the basis functions at the supports
    A = np.vstack((np.ones_like(paths[i][itm_ind], dtype=np.float), 
                   blackscholes_price(K, T - ts[i], (((i * np.average(paths[1:(i+1),[itm_ind]], axis = 0)) + ((12 -i) *paths[i][itm_ind]))/12), vol = 0.1, r=0, q=0, callput='call'))).T
    #calculate the weights for each basis function, vector B, using least squares minimization
    p = np.linalg.lstsq(A, payoff[itm_ind], rcond=None)[0]
    #calculate the continuation value per path using the constant 1 and BS put basis functions
    contval = 1 * p[0] +  blackscholes_price(K, T - ts[i], (((i * np.average(paths[1:(i+1),[itm_ind]], axis = 0)) + ((12 -i) *paths[i][itm_ind]))/12), vol = 0.1, r=0, q=0, callput='call')* p[1]

    ind = exerval >= contval
    indd = np.array(np.where(ind)[0])
    payoff[itm_ind[indd]] = exerval[ind]
    
    #add current continuation values to the overall array of continuation values
    contvals_LS = np.vstack((contvals_LS, p))
